data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Must use cooperative cancellation |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | Dead code — your rollback never fires |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed** | N/A |
| Manual `Thread` management | `BackgroundService` / `Task.Run` | Idiomatic replacement available |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;

public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        // Link the host's token with our own so either can trigger shutdown
        using var linked = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(
            stoppingToken, _cts.Token);

        while (!linked.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so GetNextItem can unblock on cancellation
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(linked.Token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, linked.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (linked.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly — no ResetAbort() needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void RequestStop() => _cts.Cancel();

    public override void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
        base.Dispose();
    }
}
```

Register it in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddHostedService<BackgroundProcessor>();
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` that blocks without a token will hang forever on shutdown.**
The old `Thread.Abort()` would force-kill a blocking call. With cooperative cancellation, your blocking method *must* accept and observe a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
// ✗ Will hang on shutdown — cannot be interrupted
var item = queue.Take();

// ✓ Throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
var item = await channel.Reader.ReadAsync(token);
// or with BlockingCollection:
var item = collection.Take(token);
```

**2. `volatile bool` is insufficient.** A `volatile bool` can't wake a thread blocked on I/O or `Take()`. `CancellationToken` integrates with async APIs and `WaitHandle` to actually interrupt blocking waits.

**3. The `Thread.Sleep(2000)` grace period** is handled automatically by the host. `BackgroundService` calls `StopAsync` with a configurable shutdown timeout:

```csharp
builder.Services.Configure<HostOptions>(opts =>
    opts.ShutdownTimeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**4. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` is silent dead code in .NET 8** — it compiles but never executes. Your rollback logic *silently disappears*. This is the most dangerous part of the migration: no compiler warning, no runtime error, just lost safety logic.

**5. If you must keep raw threads** (e.g., STA thread, COM interop), replace `Abort()` with cooperative cancellation on a `Thread`:

```csharp
private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
private Thread? _workerThread;

public void Start()
{
    _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token))
        { IsBackground = true };
    _workerThread.Start();
}

public void Stop()
{
    _cts.Cancel();
    // Join with timeout instead of Sleep + Abort
    if (_workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)) == false)
    {
        // Log warning — thread is stuck. Cannot force-kill in .NET 8.
        // Consider Environment.Exit() as last resort.
    }
}
```

The `BackgroundService` approach is strongly preferred — it integrates with DI, graceful shutdown, health checks, and `IHostApplicationLifetime` out of the box.
